[
    {
        "content": "<p>I have no clue how expensive it would be to implement, or how useful on real word projects, but one thing I've always been interested in is curry's mcc debugger: you type <code>:debug expression</code> in the REPL, which puts the expression in a queue and then this loop starts:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>pop from queue<br>\ncompute the value of the current expression<br>\nasks the user whether it's correct<br>\nif yes, <code>continue</code> loop<br>\notherwise, clear the queue and put into the queue all the function calls that went into producing the value<br>\nWhen this process ends, because the queue is empty, it means that the error is in the last expression that was expanded.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>For purely functional code it's pretty great, especially if recursive</p>",
        "id": 344479161,
        "sender_full_name": "Leonardo Taglialegne",
        "timestamp": 1679747962
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>fascinating!</p>",
        "id": 344479624,
        "sender_full_name": "Anton",
        "timestamp": 1679748113
    },
